Introduction

These are a set of research notes that help keep me on track, record my thoughts and ideas. Each of the data tables can be worked upon further (to create percentage results, for instance) or for visualisation in Tableau Public, Datawrapper etc.

We’re reading in manually cleaned data from a CSV exported from OpenRefine. The original data was scraped from the bio pages of 15 private equity firms, and the names of the educational establishments captured using Mechanical Turk.

All data requires some cleaning & “munging”, but unstructured data are harder. People went to:

  • The University of Oxford
  • Oxford University
  • Oxford
  • Balliol (a college at Oxford which considers itself prestigious)

Sometimes there are misspellings (“Carnegie Mellow University”), or technical errors (Paul Farber of TPG is so good they hired him twice - also Derek Chen.)

data = read.csv("~/Documents/Private Equity Data Harvest/openrefine/PE-Schools-2018-12-13.csv") %>%
  select(company = file,
         region,
         region2,
         name,
         education,
         school)

The companies for which we collected data are listed below in alphabetical order. n indicates the number of records per company.

data %>%
  select(company) %>%
  group_by(company) %>%
  tally()

Here’s a quick summary of the rest of the data in the 5667 records in the dataset – it’s all words, not numbers. Note that the counts beside the company names don’t represent people, but rather the number of qualifications held by the people at that firm. If you have two qualifications, you’ll appear twice in the records. An indication of this cross-over is contained in the education column. We’ll address this later.

  • We collected data on at least 3672 individuals (note - some names - e.g. Sarah Smith - are common to more than one company. This all comes out in the wash - we break down by name & company. As long as no company has hired -say- two Sarah Smiths, we should be alright)
  • There are 1151 individual schools in the dataset. Some of the longtail ones may still be incorrectly coded

Note that region and region2 were manually coded based on location data contained in the bio.

  • There are 5457 records that contain region macro-region data.
data %>% select(region) %>% filter(region != "") %>% group_by(region) %>% tally() %>% arrange(desc(n))
  • region2 is a more granular field with more missing data. Only 5098 records contain region2 data.
data %>% select(region2) %>% filter(region2 != "") %>% group_by(region2) %>% tally() %>% arrange(desc(n))

We should probably code more data for school - to enrich for region and category (e.g. to let us break out Business Schools and Law Schools as a minimum - maybe Med Schools etc as well.)

Breakdown by company & schools

Now we’ll break the dataset down by company and schools - creating a sparse matrix that shows how many qualifications from each school are held by people at each firm. That’s an ugly, but accurate sentence.

data %>%
  select(company, school) %>%
  group_by(school, company) %>%
  tally() %>%
  spread(company, n) -> 
  schools_by_company

We’ll impose some frequency order - we’ll sum the columns and the rows, and present them in descending order. The most popular school will be in the first row - and the most populous firm in the first column.

schools_by_company[order(rowSums(-schools_by_company, na.rm = TRUE)), order(colSums(-schools_by_company, na.rm = TRUE))] %>%
  select(school, everything()) ->  # quick hack to move the 'school' column into the first slot
  schools_by_company

schools_by_company

Glancing at this, there are some clear anomalies - Silver Lake, for instance. Might there be an East Coast/West Coast story to be told? We’d need to categorise US colleges by - say - timezone or state (with some further iterations on state.)

Here are the schools that feed Silver Lake

count_qualifications <- function(c){
  data %>%
  filter(company == c) %>%
  select(school) %>%
  group_by(school) %>%
  tally() %>%
  arrange(desc(n))
}

count_qualifications("silver-lake")

Summarise by an arbitrary vector of schools

It’s almost certainly going to be useful to perform something like the UC & IIT exercises above for an arbitrary, manually-selected vector (list) of schools. Let’s create that as a general function - as an example, we’ll use:

  • ESCP Europe
  • ESSEC Business School
  • European Business School
  • HEC Paris
  • INSEAD
  • London Business School
count_specific_schools <- function(s){
  data %>%
  select(company, school) %>%
  filter(str_detect(school, paste(s, collapse = "|"))) %>%
  group_by(school, company) %>%
  tally() %>%
  spread(company, n) -> 
  selected_schools

selected_schools[order(rowSums(-selected_schools, na.rm = TRUE)), 
                 order(colSums(-selected_schools, na.rm = TRUE))] %>%
  select(school, everything())
  
}

# let's test it...

schools_select <- c("INSEAD",
                    "London Business School",
                    "HEC Paris",
                    "ESCP Europe",
                    "ESSEC Business School",
                    "European Business School")

count_specific_schools(schools_select)

FT European Business Schools

The FT publishes a handy list of European Business School rankings. This could provide a great media hook for 2019 - possibly even worth talking to them ahead of time.

I’ve used a Google Sheet to capture the data and manually matched the school names in OpenRefine. Let’s read in the data and see what we can do.

read_csv("~/Documents/Private Equity Data Harvest/openrefine/FT-Top-European-Business-Schools-2018.csv") %>%
  select(school = "Reconciled Name",
         rank = "Rank 2018",
         country = "Reconciled Country") -> 
  ft_data

count_specific_schools(ft_data$school)

OK, let’s do that again, but this time rank by the FT’s preference

data %>%
  select(company, school) %>%
  group_by(school, company) %>%
  tally() %>%
  merge(ft_data)  %>%
  select(rank, everything()) %>%
  spread(company, n) %>%
  arrange(rank) -> ft_order

Adding a total column per school

ft_order %>%
  mutate(total = select(., 4:18) %>% rowSums(na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  select(rank, school, country, total, everything())

We can split out the UK schools

ft_order %>%
  filter(country == "UK") %>%
  mutate(total = select(., 4:18) %>% rowSums(na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  select(rank, school, country, total, everything())

Or the French schools

ft_order %>%
  filter(country == "France") %>%
  mutate(total = select(., 4:18) %>% rowSums(na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  select(rank, school, country, total, everything())

Or the Scandi schools

ft_order %>%
  filter(country == "Sweden"| country == "Denmark" |country == "Norway"| country == "Finland") %>%
  mutate(total = select(., 4:18) %>% rowSums(na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  select(rank, school, country, total, everything())

schools_by_region[order(rowSums(-schools_by_region, na.rm = TRUE)), order(colSums(-schools_by_region, na.rm = TRUE))] %>%

schools_by_region

We’ll adapt that general-purpose function for looking at a subset of schools

count_specific_schools_region <- function(s){
  data %>%
  select(school, region2) %>%
  filter(region2 != "") %>%
  filter(str_detect(school, paste(s, collapse = "|"))) %>%
  group_by(school, region2) %>%
  tally() %>%
  spread(region2, n) -> 
  selected_schools_region

selected_schools_region[order(rowSums(-selected_schools_region, na.rm = TRUE)), 
                 order(colSums(-selected_schools_region, na.rm = TRUE))] %>%
  select(school, everything())
  
}

People-based views (In Progress)

Up until now, we’ve been looking at this in terms of “degrees” and not “people.” Most of the people have more than one degree:

data %>%
  select(education) %>%
  group_by(education) %>%
  tally() %>%
  spread(education, n) %>%
  mutate("single degree" = school1 - (school2 + school3),
         "two degrees" = school2 - school3,
         "three or more" = school3) %>%
  select(-starts_with("school"))

Let’s break that down by company – who employs the most eggheads?

data %>%
  select(company, education) %>%
  group_by(company, education) %>%
  tally() %>%
  spread(education, n) %>%
  mutate("single degree" = school1 - (school2 + school3),
         "two degrees" = school2 - school3,
         "three or more" = school3) %>%
  select(-starts_with("school")) %>%
  arrange(desc(`three or more`))  # backticks fix whitespace

We really need to look at this in terms of percentages

Network Graph Visualisation (In Progress)

We need to create a list of edges - there’s a simple way and a complex way. The simple way may actually be more accurate - select the school and company - graph that.

Build out vertices & edges data

We’ll append an “organisation type” column for later aesthetics

vertices <- rbind(tibble(label = levels(data$company), orgtype = "company"),
      tibble(label = levels(data$school), orgtype = "school"))

vertices

and the edges…

data %>%
  select(source = school, target = company) %>%
  group_by(source, target) %>%
  tally() %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  rename(weight = n) ->
  edges

edges

We can write the nodes & edges to csv for import to Gephi
